      <h2>What Is an Ionizing Bar?</h2>
      <p>
        An <strong>ionizing bar</strong> — also called an <strong>ion bar</strong>, <strong>ionizer bar</strong>, or <strong>static elimination bar</strong> — is a long, slender device mounted close to a moving surface that emits a balanced stream of positive and negative ions to neutralize electrostatic charge. As a charged surface passes beneath or alongside the bar, the ions of opposite polarity are attracted to the charge, neutralizing it without physical contact.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Ionizing bars</strong> are used throughout electronics, display, optical film, and packaging manufacturing wherever static charge causes defects, contamination, or handling problems. They are passive devices — they do not require the material to be grounded — which makes them effective on insulators like plastic film, polarizer sheets, glass panels, and PCB laminates.
      </p>

      <div style="background:#f8f9fa;border-left:4px solid #f5c400;padding:18px 24px;border-radius:6px;margin:28px 0;">
        <strong>Quick definition:</strong> An ionizing bar converts high voltage into a cloud of balanced positive and negative air ions using corona discharge from an array of emitter needles. Those ions flow onto nearby charged surfaces and neutralize the static charge.
      </div>

      <h2>How Does an Ionizing Bar Work?</h2>
      <p>
        Every <strong>ionization bar</strong> operates on the principle of <strong>corona discharge</strong>. A high-voltage power supply — typically AC or DC at several kilovolts — is applied to an array of sharp emitter needles along the length of the bar. The intense electric field at the needle tips strips electrons from air molecules, creating both positive ions (molecules that lost electrons) and negative ions (molecules that gained electrons).
      </p>
      <p>
        This ion cloud drifts away from the bar toward nearby surfaces. When those surfaces carry a static charge:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>A <strong>negatively charged</strong> surface attracts positive ions — the charge is neutralized</li>
        <li>A <strong>positively charged</strong> surface attracts negative ions — the charge is neutralized</li>
        <li>When charge balance is reached, no further ions are absorbed — the process is self-regulating</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The result is a surface with near-zero electrostatic potential, typically reduced to ±10–100V depending on bar type, distance, and line speed.
      </p>

      <h3>Key Components of an Ionizer Bar</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Emitter needles</strong> — tungsten, stainless steel, or carbon-tipped pins spaced along the bar. Needle sharpness and spacing determine ion density and effective coverage width</li>
        <li><strong>High-voltage power supply</strong> — generates the corona discharge voltage. AC supplies produce both ion polarities simultaneously from each needle; DC supplies alternate polarity between needles or in pulses</li>
        <li><strong>Shielding and housing</strong> — a grounded outer housing shapes the ion flow and protects personnel from the high-voltage internals</li>
        <li><strong>Self-diagnostic system</strong> — found on intelligent ion bars, monitors ion balance and alerts when emitter needles are contaminated or worn</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Types of Ionizing Bars</h2>
      <p>
        Not all <strong>ionizer bars</strong> work the same way. The three main categories differ in their power supply type, ion balance method, and performance characteristics.
      </p>

      <h3>1. AC Ionizing Bars</h3>
      <p>
        AC ionizing bars apply alternating current to the emitter needles. Each needle produces both positive and negative ions in each half-cycle. AC bars are simple, cost-effective, and reliable — but ion balance can drift over time as needles contaminate unevenly. Residual charge levels are typically ±10–50V.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> general industrial applications, packaging lines, moderate speed conveyors, applications where cost is a primary consideration.</p>

      <h3>2. DC Pulsed Ionizing Bars</h3>
      <p>
        DC pulsed ionizing bars alternate positive and negative high-voltage pulses, with separate needle rows for each polarity. This allows independent adjustment of positive and negative ion output, enabling precise balance correction for offset charge conditions. Residual charge is typically ±5–20V. DC bars often include self-diagnostic feedback.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> precision electronics, display panel manufacturing, optical film lamination, applications with varying charge polarity, high-speed lines.</p>

      <h3>3. Intelligent / Smart Ionizing Bars</h3>
      <p>
        Intelligent <strong>ionizing bars</strong> — such as the DGSDK ST-G Series — combine DC pulsed ionization with real-time self-diagnostic monitoring. Sensors detect ion balance imbalance and contaminated needles. An indicator alerts operators when cleaning or replacement is needed. Some models communicate with line control systems via digital outputs.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> critical production lines, display and semiconductor manufacturing, applications where undetected static spikes cause costly yield loss.</p>

      <h2>Ionizing Bar vs. Other Static Elimination Methods</h2>
