      <p>
        The key advantage of an <strong>ionizing bar static eliminator</strong> over grounding methods is that it works on non-conductive materials. Film, glass, plastic, and optical substrates cannot be grounded — ions are the only way to neutralize charge on these surfaces.
      </p>

      <h2>Where Are Ionizing Bars Used?</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Ionizer bars</strong> are used wherever a moving insulating surface carries static charge that causes contamination, attraction, mis-feeding, or discharge damage. Typical applications include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Display panel manufacturing</strong> — neutralizing charge on polarizer film, glass panels, and optical films before lamination and bonding to prevent particle attraction and bright-spot defects</li>
        <li><strong>PCB and FPC manufacturing</strong> — eliminating static from copper foil, laminates, and flexible substrates before printing, imaging, and lamination</li>
        <li><strong>SMT production lines</strong> — neutralizing charge from PCB substrates and component reels before placement to prevent mis-pickup and component shift</li>
        <li><strong>Packaging lines</strong> — preventing film cling, mis-feeding, and label mis-application on plastic packaging lines</li>
        <li><strong>Printing and converting</strong> — eliminating static from web materials that causes ink misting, mis-registration, and sheet sticking</li>
        <li><strong>Semiconductor and wafer handling</strong> — protecting bare die and sensitive devices from electrostatic discharge during wafer-level and back-end processes</li>
        <li><strong>Optical film and sheet processing</strong> — removing charge from diffusion films, prism sheets, and protective films before inspection and lamination</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to Select the Right Ionizing Bar</h2>
      <p>
        Choosing the wrong <strong>ion bar</strong> results in poor static elimination performance, increased defect rates, or premature emitter wear. Consider these five factors when specifying an ionizing bar:
      </p>

      <h3>1. Coverage Length</h3>
      <p>
        Ionizing bars are available in standard lengths from 150mm to 1,500mm and in custom lengths for wide-format applications. The bar must cover the full width of the substrate being neutralized, with a small margin on each side. For web materials, the bar length should match or slightly exceed web width.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Working Distance</h3>
      <p>
        Most <strong>ionization bars</strong> are rated for a working distance of 25–300mm from the surface. Residual charge level increases with working distance. For applications requiring low residual charge (below ±20V), keep the working distance below 50–100mm and use a DC pulsed bar.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Line Speed</h3>
      <p>
        At higher conveyor or web speeds, the exposure time beneath the ionizing bar decreases. A bar that achieves ±20V residual at 10 m/min may only achieve ±50V at 50 m/min. For high-speed lines, use multiple bars in series, increase ion output (higher voltage or more needles), or reduce working distance.
      </p>

      <h3>4. AC vs. DC</h3>
      <p>
        Use <strong>AC ionizing bars</strong> for general applications where tight ion balance is not critical. Use <strong>DC pulsed ionizing bars</strong> for display, optical film, and semiconductor applications where residual charge must be minimized and ion balance must be tunable. Intelligent bars with self-diagnostic capability are recommended for critical production lines.
      </p>

      <h3>5. Environment</h3>
      <p>
        In cleanroom environments, select bars with smooth, sealed housings that do not trap particles. In high-humidity environments, condensation on emitter needles can cause arcing — bars with protective housings and elevated operating temperature ratings are preferred. In dusty or contaminated environments, select bars with accessible emitter needle arrays for easy cleaning.
      </p>

      <h2>Maintenance: Keeping Your Ionizer Bar Performing</h2>
      <p>
        Emitter needles accumulate contamination from dust, oil mist, and process residues over time. Contaminated needles produce fewer ions and may produce imbalanced ion output, leaving residual charge on the substrate. Maintenance intervals depend on the operating environment:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Clean-room conditions</strong> — inspect and clean emitter needles every 3–6 months</li>
        <li><strong>Standard factory conditions</strong> — inspect monthly, clean every 1–3 months</li>
        <li><strong>Dusty or oil-mist environments</strong> — inspect weekly, clean as needed</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        To clean emitter needles: power off the bar and disconnect the high-voltage supply. Wipe needles gently with a clean, dry cotton swab or brush. Do not use solvent directly on needle tips. Intelligent ionizing bars (such as the DGSDK ST-G Series) include a contamination indicator that alerts operators when cleaning is needed, eliminating guesswork.
      </p>

