      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What is the difference between an ionizing bar and an ionizing blower?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">An <strong>ionizing bar</strong> is a long, linear device designed to neutralize static across the full width of a moving surface — a web, panel, or substrate on a conveyor. It provides coverage along a line. An ionizing blower (fan) generates ions that are carried by an airflow to a specific area or point. Blowers are used on workbenches and for component handling; ionizing bars are used on production lines where material passes beneath or alongside the bar.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How close does an ionizing bar need to be to work?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Most ionizing bars work best at 25–150mm from the target surface. At longer distances, ion concentration decreases and residual charge increases. Standard DC pulsed bars achieve ±20–50V residual at 50–100mm. Long-range ionizing bars (such as the ST-F Series) are designed for working distances up to 300–400mm where close mounting is not possible.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Is an ionizing bar safe to touch?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">The emitter needles and internal components operate at several kilovolts — direct contact with internal components is dangerous. However, the ion cloud emitted from the bar is safe to touch. The housing is grounded and the ion current at the surface is extremely low (microamps). Industrial ionizing bars include safety features — the high voltage automatically disconnects if the housing is opened.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">How do I know if my ionizing bar is working?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Use a static field meter (surface voltmeter) to measure residual charge on the substrate after the bar. A properly functioning bar should reduce charge to below ±100V in most applications, and below ±20V for precision applications. Intelligent ionizing bars include built-in indicators that show ion balance status and alert when performance degrades. If your bar lacks this feature, schedule monthly testing with a field meter.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">What causes an ionizing bar to fail or lose effectiveness?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">The most common cause is emitter needle contamination. Dust, oil mist, and process residues coat the needle tips over time, reducing ion output. Cleaning needles with a dry cotton swab typically restores performance. Other causes include power supply failure, damaged shielding, and broken emitter needles. Intelligent ionizing bars with self-diagnostic capability detect needle contamination before it causes production defects.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3 class="faq-question">Can one ionizing bar cover the full width of my line?</h3>
          <p class="faq-answer">Standard ionizing bars are available in lengths up to 1,500mm and can be linked end-to-end for wider applications. For a 1,800mm wide optical film line, two 900mm bars or one 1,800mm custom bar would be used. DGSDK produces ionizing bars in custom lengths to match specific line widths. Contact us with your substrate width and conveyor speed to confirm the appropriate bar length and configuration.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

